{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Latent Variables — concept overview"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Observed vs. Latent"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "In a probabilistic generative model, some variables are observable — you see them in the dataset — and others are latent, existing only inside the model. Latent variables encode structure that explains the observations without being directly measured. The model asserts that observations were generated by first sampling some latent code z and then sampling x conditional on z:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "z \\sim p(z), \\quad x \\sim p(x \\mid z)"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "This is a generative story. The marginal probability of an observation is the integral (or sum) over all possible latent codes:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "p(x) = \\int p(x \\mid z)\\, p(z)\\, dz"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why Introduce Latent Variables?"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Latent variables allow simple component distributions to be combined into rich, multimodal marginals. A GMM is the clearest example: each component Gaussian is unimodal, but the marginal p(x) = Σₖ πₖ N(x;μₖ,Σₖ) can have multiple peaks. The discrete cluster label k is the latent variable; it is never observed, only inferred."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "More broadly, latent variables let a model disentangle different factors of variation:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Face images:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " z might separately encode identity, pose, and lighting, while x is the pixel array."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Text:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " z might encode the latent topic or writing style; x is the sequence of words."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Speech:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " z is the phoneme sequence (HMM hidden states); x is the acoustic feature frames."}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Posterior: Inference Problem"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Given an observed x, you often want to know which latent values z most likely produced it. This requires the posterior distribution:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "p(z \\mid x) = \\frac{p(x \\mid z)\\, p(z)}{p(x)}"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The denominator p(x) = ∫ p(x|z) p(z) dz is the marginal likelihood — also called the evidence. For most interesting models this integral is intractable: z is high-dimensional and p(x|z) p(z) is not a distribution with a known closed-form integral. This intractability is the fundamental obstacle in latent variable modelling, and it motivates variational inference (the ELBO) and MCMC methods."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Discrete vs. Continuous Latent Variables"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Property"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Discrete z"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Continuous z"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Prior p(z)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Categorical (e.g. uniform over K)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Gaussian N(0, I) or other"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Marginal p(x)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Finite sum (often feasible)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Integral (usually intractable)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Typical model"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "GMM, HMM, LDA"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "VAE, normalising flows"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Inference method"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "EM, sum-product"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "ELBO / amortised VI, MCMC"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Concrete Example: 1-D Gaussian Mixture"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import numpy as np\n\n# Generative model: discrete z ~ Categorical, x | z ~ Gaussian\nrng = np.random.default_rng(42)\n\npi   = np.array([0.4, 0.35, 0.25])   # mixture weights\nmu   = np.array([-3.0, 0.0, 4.0])    # component means\nsigma = np.array([0.8, 1.2, 0.6])    # component std devs\n\nN = 1000\n# Step 1: sample latent cluster assignments\nz = rng.choice(len(pi), size=N, p=pi)\n# Step 2: sample observations given cluster\nx = mu[z] + sigma[z] * rng.standard_normal(N)\n\nprint(f\"x shape: {x.shape}, mean: {x.mean():.2f}, std: {x.std():.2f}\")\n# Even though each component is Gaussian, the marginal p(x) is trimodal.\n\n# Posterior for one point x=0.5:\nx_obs = 0.5\nlog_likelihoods = -0.5 * ((x_obs - mu) / sigma) ** 2 - np.log(sigma)\nlog_posterior   = np.log(pi) + log_likelihoods\nlog_posterior  -= np.max(log_posterior)   # numeric stability\nposterior = np.exp(log_posterior) / np.exp(log_posterior).sum()\nfor k, p in enumerate(posterior):\n    print(f\"P(z={k} | x=0.5) = {p:.3f}\")   # cluster 2 (mean=0) dominates"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Training: Maximum Marginal Likelihood"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Learning the parameters θ of a latent variable model means maximising the marginal log-likelihood of the observed data:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\mathcal{L}(\\theta) = \\sum_{n=1}^{N} \\log p_\\theta(x_n) = \\sum_{n=1}^{N} \\log \\int p_\\theta(x_n \\mid z)\\, p(z)\\, dz"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The log of an integral has no simple gradient in general — the expectation-maximisation (EM) algorithm and the evidence lower bound (ELBO) are two approaches that sidestep this by introducing an auxiliary distribution over z. Both exploit the same algebraic identity that decomposes the log-marginal into a tractable lower bound plus a KL divergence term."}]}]}}